Fig 14.12 Xanthelasma. Xanthos is Greek for yellow, and elasma means plate. Xanthelasmata are 
lipid- laden yellow plaques, typically a few millimetres wide. They congregate around the lids, or 
just below the eyes, and signify hyperlipidaemia.

(See ﬁg 16.37.) First choice in renal colic. Performed without IV contrast so safe 
in renal impairment; such unenhanced images miss <2% of stones, but can show 
other pathologies. With IV contrast, CT can delineate masses (cystic or solid, contrast enhancement, calciﬁcation, local/ distant extension, renal vein involvement); 
assess renal trauma (presence of two kidneys; haemorrhage; devascularization; 
laceration; urine leak); and show retroperitoneal lesions. CT urogram has all but 
replaced IV urography and the radiation dose is similar.
